ldt   or its variant <b>Langfeld</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Longfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places called with Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’, such as Longfield, in Kent, Longfield in Todmorden, Yorkshire, and Longfield Wood in Laughton, Sussex. Compare   Langfield  .","English: in some cases, possibly also a variant of <b>Longville</b>, a habitational name from Longueville-la-Gifart, now Longueville-sur-Scie (Seine-Maritime), brought to England by the Normans.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Danish   Langfeldt   or its German variant <b>Langfeld</b>."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":25,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Langfield was born in 1357, in Woolley, Yorkshire, England, her father, Henry De Langfield, was 28 and her mother, Agnes Vavasour, was 31. She married Sir John Woodruffe about 1378, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1384, in her hometown, at the age of 27, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1357–1384":"1357–1384","1356–1397":"1356–1397","1343–1434":"1343–1434","1381–1400":"1381–1400","1382–1430":"1382–1430","1384–1430":"1384–1430","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1327–1384":"1327–1384","about 1381":"umbes 1381","1330":"1330"